I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation to be able to connect with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
one plunged directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
without having any reason to question the pedestal on which they placed us, parasocial relationships had become the foundations for our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified private locations.
unconsciously, one is dying to connect with the universal community surrounding all of this
That's why so many of us are obsessed with shows like The Office or movies like Mr. Speaker, which are full of short references, just like memes.
we repeated these references, knowing that most people already knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, you can't know if everyone has seen it.
there's too much to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape hypersaturation?
we get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to eventually realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art to which we connect can be very imperfect.
one enters into para-social relationships by paying more attention.
one understands that it is hard to reach such positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
Due to the lack of collective awareness in the media, a class consciousness has developed that helps us remain critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
We are in a turbulent period and I can't wait to find out where it will take us.
